<font color="#FF0000">OUR NATION'S HONOR</font><br>
<tt>Mon Oct 12 21:00:10 US/Eastern 1998
</tt><p>
It has been months since I last visited this site. We lost a lot when this site was shut down, but by some twist of fate, by the shadow of fate, I have been able to get on just this one more time. <br><br>
I was not here during the last days before the days of sharing and caring were brought to a halt. I miss those days. Four of us still continue to communicate with each other, Bob, Ed, Art and myself. The book I've been writing is almost complete, it should be send out to the publishers by the end of this year. Being here among friends was an encouragement and kept me writing. That journey has been long, painful and interesting.<br><br>
I have now found 33 of the original 47 Marines I served with in Vietnam. Some of us have met several times and all of us hope to come together this next year. Some of us had not seen each other for over 30 years. <br><br>
I learned a lot about myself from those friends I served with in Viet Nam. I learned a lot about what I did 30 years ago as a young Marine machine gunner in the jungles of South East Asia. I realized that I served with some very honorable men, brave men who were willing to die for what we believed in. I realized how much respect we had for each other then and even now, thirty years later how honorable it is to recapture that trust and unity.<br><br>
War is like that; it brings individuals together, makes them one, and then tears them apart. Of the thirty-three men that served in my combat unit. 1st platoon, India Company 3/7, only two have any lingering PTSD problems, both of them were captured by the enemy, and we went back and rescued them. The others have outstanding jobs, and families with normal troubles but nothing really disturbing. One common denominator is that we all stayed silent and have remained that way until we saw each other and were within minutes able to once again capture those times, memories.  What a different world it would have been had America honored its Viet Nam servicemen.<br><br>
Since anyone last posted here, our nation has changed, honor, trust, justice have been seriously compromised, by our national leaders. We are a nation adrift in a sea of guilt, shame and sorrow. I fear what awaits us as we move toward the turn of the century. Once again I feel betrayed by those entrusted with higher power who have failed once again to do what they know is right. <br><br>
To all of you that have posted here in the past and to those of you now reading this message. <br>
This site was important; it meant a lot and it also gave the world an inside look at the heart and mind of those who served without honor. <br><br>
Today we’re once again at the doorways of destruction, with our military men gearing up for battle in a land we don’t belong. With our nation’s shame before us I fear what tomorrows battles will bring. I salute those in uniform in the past, present and future. You have my respect and if ever need a listening ear; Ed Bob Art Duke and I are still here in the shadows of America’s spirit.<br><br>
I am Cook <br>

